"1035":"1035","1056":"1056","about 1058":"circa 1058","about 1035":"circa 1035","2 October 1056":"2 oktober 1056","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Europe":"Europa"},"en":{"about 1035–":"about 1035–Deceased","1037–Female":"1037–Deceased","1056–1127":"1056–1127","1058–Female":"1058–Deceased","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","1035–Male":"1035–Deceased","about 1060":"about 1060","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1037":"1037","1058":"1058","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","about 1058":"about 1058","about 1035":"about 1035","2 October 1056":"2 October 1056","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Europe":"Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wheaten","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Whiddon  .","History: Robert Wheaton came from England to Rehoboth, MA, <i>c.</i> 1636."],"variants":[{"name":"Whiddon","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of numerous minor places in Devon named Whiddon. Some are named with Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ or <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’; others with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> or <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":0,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":31,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":51,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":61,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":71,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Richard I Wheaten was born about 1035, in Yorkshire, England. He had at least 3 daughters with Gunnora Haraldsdotter."},"et":{"about 1035–":"umbes 1035–Surnud","1037–Female":"1037–Surnud","1056–1127":"1056–1127","1058–Female":"1058–Surnud","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1035–Male":"1035–Surnud","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1037":"1037","1058":"1058","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","about 1058":"umbes 1058","about 1035":"umbes 1035","2 October 1056":"2. oktoober 1056","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"about 1035–":"noin 1035–Kuollut","1037–Female":"1037–Kuollut","1056–1127":"1056–1127","1058–Female":"1058–Kuollut","1060–Female":"1060–Kuollut","1035–Male":"1035–Kuollut","about 1060":"noin 1060","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1037":"1037","1058":"1058","1035":"1035","1056":"1056","about 1058":"noin 1058","about 1035":"noin 1035","2 October 1056":"2. lokakuuta 1056","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Europe":"Europe"},"fr":{"about 1035–":"environ 1035–Décédé","1037–Female":"1037–Décéd